SIMPLE: impulsive
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Impulsive
<hw>Im*pul"sive</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[Cf. F.
<ets>impulsif</ets>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Having the power of driving or impelling; giving an
impulse; moving; impellent.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Poor men! poor papers! We and they⟦br⟧
Do some <qex>impulsive</qex> force obey.</q>
<rj><qau>Prior.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Actuated by impulse or by transient
feelings.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>My heart, <qex>impulsive</qex> and wayward.</q>
<rj><qau>Longfellow.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Mech.)</fld> <def>Acting momentarily, or by
impulse; not continuous; -- said of forces.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Impulsive</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Impulsive
<hw>Im*pul"sive</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>That which impels
or gives an impulse; an impelling agent.</def> <rj><au>Sir W.
Wotton.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Impulsively</ent>⟦br⟧
